# Trivy vulnerability waivers for the Timelapse Manager runtime image.
#
# The release pipeline scans the built linux/amd64 image and FAILS the release
# gate on any unresolved HIGH or CRITICAL finding. This file is the documented
# waiver path: each entry suppresses one finding that has been reviewed and
# judged not to apply (e.g. a false positive, or a CVE in a component the app
# never exercises).
#
# Rules:
#   * One CVE ID per line (e.g. CVE-2024-12345). Blank lines and #-comments are
#     ignored by Trivy.
#   * Every waiver MUST carry a comment: who reviewed it, the date, and WHY it
#     does not apply. An unexplained waiver is treated as a review defect.
#   * Prefer fixing (bump the base image / dependency) over waiving. Waivers are
#     for findings with no available fix that are genuinely not reachable.
#   * Re-review waivers at each release; remove any that a base-image bump has
#     resolved so the list does not rot.
#
# Format example (keep entries below this line):
#
#   # CVE-2024-00000 -- <reviewer>, 2026-06-10. Affects <pkg> codepath X, which
#   #   this image never invokes (no <feature>); no fixed version published.
#   CVE-2024-00000
#
# The release gate runs with ignore-unfixed=true, so unfixable distro CVEs in the
# slim base (perl-base, zlib1g, libsqlite3, ncurses, etc.) are tracked-not-blocked
# without per-CVE entries here. This file is therefore reserved for the rare case
# of a FIXABLE HIGH/CRITICAL that is a reviewed false positive.
#
# (No active waivers.)
